717378f-a.text:
Broadway at the N. E. corner of W. 29th Street (right), showing the Casper Samler Farmhouse at this site. This was replaced in the 80's by the famous Gilsey House. This structure still stands in 1939 as a combined office and loft building.
circa 1870
Collection of George T. Bagoe

717377f-a.text:
Broadway, north from W. 29th Street. Intersection in the foreground is 3Oth Street with the Hofbramhans to the south and Wallseks Theatre to the north. Beyond the latter are the (new) Grand, the Imperial and the ? hotels. To the left is Dalys Theatre. In the background, across the Sixth Avenue "El" at Herald Square, appears the then prominent Times Building.

December 1904

Geo. L. Balgue

717376f-a.text:
The old Gilsey House, now serving as an office building, Broadway at the N.E. corner of 29th Street. The Gilsey House, although not a large hotel, was famous for its comfort and the excellence of its cuisine. Its dining room was said to be one of the half a dozen which could be mentioned in the same breath with Delmonico's. It was built in the early 1870's, and was converted into an office building
between 1910 and 1916. It will still stand in 1936.
June 2, 1928.
P. L. Sperr.
